# Modal Stack

Config-driven infrastructure for deploying OpenAI-compatible LLM inference endpoints on [Modal](https://modal.com/) using vLLM.

## Project Structure

```
modal-stack/
  cli.py               # `modalstack` console script (deploy / run subcommands)
  main.py              # Modal entrypoint (loads config, wires up Modal app)
  configs/             # Per-model YAML configs (one file per deployment)
    gemma4_26b.yaml    # Example: Gemma 4 26B on H200
    _example.yaml      # Annotated template for adding new models
  schemas/             # JSON Schema (source of truth for config shape)
  models/              # Core Python package
    _generated.py      # Auto-generated Pydantic models (do not edit)
    config.py          # ModelConfig + from_yaml / validators
    image.py           # Modal container Image factory (vLLM, future SGLang)
    server.py          # AppResources factory + vLLM command builder
    health.py          # Health check local_entrypoint
```

## How It Works

1. User specifies a config: `modalstack deploy <name>` (or `modal deploy main.py` with `MODEL_CONFIG`)
2. `main.py` loads `configs/<name>.yaml` and validates via Pydantic
3. `models/server.py` builds the Modal App with GPU, volumes, and vLLM command
4. Modal deploys the container with an OpenAI-compatible API endpoint

## Key Commands

```bash
modalstack deploy <name>          # Deploy to Modal
modalstack run <name>             # Spin up + health check
modalstack generate-config        # Regenerate models/_generated.py from schema
modalstack generate-docs          # Regenerate README config reference from schema
```

## Adding a New Model

1. Create `configs/<model_name>.yaml` (only `model.name` is required; see `_example.yaml`)
2. Deploy with `modalstack deploy <model_name>`

## Editing Guidelines

- **Config schema changes** go in `schemas/model-config.schema.json`, then run `modalstack generate-config` and `modalstack generate-docs`
- **Custom config behavior** (e.g. `from_yaml`, default `app_name`) goes in `models/config.py` only
- **Container image logic** goes in `models/image.py` (dispatches on `engine.type`)
- **vLLM command construction** lives in `models/server.py` (`_build_vllm_cmd`)
- **New engine support** (e.g. SGLang): add to `image.py`, `server.py`, and extend the `Literal` in `config.py`
- **Never hardcode model-specific values** in Python -- put them in YAML configs

## Dependencies

Managed via `pyproject.toml`: `modal`, `aiohttp`, `pyyaml`, `pydantic`. Install with `pip install -e .` or `pip install -r requirements.txt`.
